<DOC><DOCNO>WSJ911120-0001</DOCNO><DOCID>911120-0001.</DOCID><HL>   Bonneville to Report   Third-Quarter Loss,   Is in Default on Debt</HL><DATE>11/20/91</DATE><SO>WALL STREET JOURNAL (J), NO PAGE CITATION</SO><CO>   BPCO</CO><MS>INDUSTRIAL (IDU)</MS><IN>HEAVY CONSTRUCTION; INDUSTRIAL AND COMMERCIAL (CON)</IN><NS>EARNINGS PROJECTIONS (ERP)RESTRUCTURINGS, RECAPITALIZATION (RCN)</NS><RE>NORTH AMERICA (NME)UNITED STATES (US)UTAH (UT)</RE><LP>   Bonneville Pacific Corp. said it will report athird-quarter loss after asset writedowns of as much as $35million, and the company disclosed that it is in technicaldefault on $130.5 million of debt.   Bonneville, a Salt Lake City-based developer and operatorof power plants, also said the recent withdrawal of financialsupport by its largest shareholder, Portland General Corp.,caused a delay in its filing of its third-quarter resultswith the Securities and Exchange Commission.</LP><TEXT>   Bonneville probably will write off &quot;up to $25 million to$35 million&quot; on certain energy cogeneration projects, saidRobert L. Wood, president and chief executive officer.   After Portland General said last week that it would writeoff its entire $45 million investment in Bonneville and stopfurther financial support, Bonneville said it would &quot;assessalternatives&quot; including a &quot;significant restructuring,&quot; filingunder Chapter 11 of the federal Bankruptcy Code or seeking asubstantial investment from another party.   Bonneville said it is in violation of covenants related tocertain long-term debt obligations. The defaults havetriggered cross-default provisions in other agreements, thecompany said. The amount of debt that could become due ondemand as a result of the defaults is about $130.5 million,including $28 million to Portland General, Bonneville said.   Mr. Woods said the company has about $63 million ofconvertible subordinated debentures and owes about $25million to Chase Manhattan Bank. The balance is held by otherbanks and small creditors, he said. The only overdueobligation is a $3.4 million bank credit line, Mr. Wood said.The next payment to debenture holders is due in February.</TEXT></DOC>